First, make sure to install the `pugixml` library if you haven't already. You can download it from its [official website](https://pugixml.org/download.html) or install it via a package manager like `apt` on Debian-based systems:

```sh
sudo apt-get install libpugixml-dev
```

Next, include the necessary headers and link the library in your C++ project:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <pugixml.hpp>

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugi::xml_document doc;
    pugi::xml_node root;

    // Load the markdown into the XML document
    if (doc.load_string(markdown.c_str())) {
        root = doc.document_element();
        // Convert the XML document to a string
        std::ostringstream oss;
        root.print(oss, pugi::format_html);
        return oss.str();
    } else {
        // If parsing fails, return the original markdown
        return markdown;
    }
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello World\nThis is a markdown text.";
    std::string html = convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);
    std::cout << "Markdown:\n" << markdown << "\n\nHTML:\n" << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this example:

1. We include the necessary headers for `std::string`, `iostream`, and `pugixml`.
2. The `convertMarkdownToHTML` function takes a const reference to a `std::string` containing markdown text.
3. We use `pugi::xml_document` to parse the markdown text.
4. If the markdown text parses successfully, we convert the parsed XML document to an HTML string using `root.print(oss, pugi::format_html)`.
5. If the parsing fails, we return the original markdown text.
6. In the `main` function, we demonstrate the usage of the `convertMarkdownToHTML` function.

